# Client Deployment Playbook

## Client Repo Structure (`exodus-client-template`)

```
{client-name}/
├── exodus.yml              # Master client config
├── review-standards/
│   └── client.yml          # BLOCK/WARN/NOTE rules for this client
├── knowledge-base/
│   └── domain.md           # Domain context injected into agent prompts
├── ironlayer/              # Client-specific IronLayer models and overrides
│   └── clients/{client}/   # Custom dbt models, sources, seeds
└── terraform/
    └── client.tfvars       # Per-client Terraform variable overrides
```

## Transformation Framework Selection

Exodus supports three transformation frameworks. Determine which one the client uses during onboarding:

| Framework | Auto-detect Signal | IronLayer Flag |
|-----------|--------------------|----------------|
| **dbt Core** | `dbt_project.yml` present | `--framework dbt` |
| **SQLMesh** | `config.yaml` + `MODEL(` blocks in `.sql` files | `--framework sqlmesh` |
| **Raw SQL** | Neither of the above | `--framework raw` |

Run `ironlayer plan --framework auto .` during Phase 2 — it will auto-detect and confirm the framework. All IronLayer governance capabilities (cost, risk, lineage, safety, PR review) work regardless of framework.

**Framework-specific resources:**
- **dbt Core:** See `dbt-sql.mdc` rule + `exodus-dbt-model` skill
- **dbt Cloud Enterprise:** See `dbt-cloud.mdc` rule + `exodus-dbt-cloud` skill
- **SQLMesh:** See `sqlmesh.mdc` rule + `exodus-sqlmesh` skill

## `exodus.yml` — Client Config Schema

```yaml
client:
  id: client-alpha
  name: "Client Alpha"
  transformation_framework: dbt       # dbt | sqlmesh | raw | auto (default: auto)
  databricks:
    host: "https://xxx.azuredatabricks.net"
    warehouse_id: "abc123"           # SQL Warehouse (user-facing queries only)
    job_compute:                     # Job compute for CI/CD (cheapest)
      node_type: "i3.xlarge"
      min_workers: 1
      max_workers: 4
  unity_catalog:
    raw_catalog: "client_alpha_raw"
    prod_catalog: "client_alpha_prod"
    ci_catalog:  "client_alpha_ci"   # Used for dbt clients; SQLMesh uses Virtual Environments
  review:
    block_threshold: 70              # confidence < 70 → Request Changes
    standards_file: "review-standards/client.yml"
    pass2_enabled: true              # Two-pass review (Pro tier)
  platform_version: "2.0.0"         # Pinned Exodus Foundation version
```

## `review-standards/client.yml` — Review Rules

```yaml
# Inherits from exodus-autopilot/review-standards/default.yml
# Override or add rules specific to this client
# Framework-specific sections: dbt, sqlmesh, sql, terraform

rules:
  dbt:                               # Only applied for dbt clients
    - id: CLIENT-001
      severity: BLOCK
      description: "All fact tables must have a grain comment in the model config"
      pattern: "fct_*.sql missing grain comment"

    - id: CLIENT-002
      severity: WARN
      description: "Staging models should not contain business logic"

  sqlmesh:                           # Only applied for SQLMesh clients
    - id: CLIENT-SM-001
      severity: BLOCK
      description: "INCREMENTAL_BY_UNIQUE_KEY models must define grain in MODEL DDL"

    - id: CLIENT-SM-002
      severity: WARN
      description: "All INCREMENTAL models must define owner in MODEL DDL"

  sql:
    - id: CLIENT-SQL-001
      severity: BLOCK
      description: "Raw division is not allowed — use {{ safe_divide() }} (dbt) or @safe_divide() (sqlmesh)"

  terraform:
    - id: CLIENT-TF-001
      severity: BLOCK
      description: "All S3 buckets must have versioning enabled"
```

## Onboarding Checklist

### Phase 1: Infrastructure (Days 1-2)
- [ ] Create client in `exodus-terraform/clients/{client}.tf`
- [ ] `terraform apply` — creates GitHub repo, Databricks catalogs, S3 bucket, IAM roles
- [ ] Validate Unity Catalog topology: raw / prod / ci catalogs
- [ ] Configure GitHub App installation for client repo

### Phase 2: Data Stack (Days 3-4)
- [ ] Copy `exodus-client-template` → client's new repo
- [ ] Fill in `exodus.yml` with client's Databricks details and `transformation_framework`
- [ ] Run `ironlayer plan --framework auto .` — confirm framework detection
- [ ] **If dbt:** Configure `profiles.yml`; run `dbt build --target dev` to validate connectivity
- [ ] **If SQLMesh:** Configure `config.yaml` gateway; run `sqlmesh plan dev` to validate connectivity
- [ ] Configure source extractors (Coinbase, HubSpot, or client-specific)

### Phase 3: AI Review (Day 5)
- [ ] Fill in `review-standards/client.yml` with client-specific rules (include `sqlmesh:` section if SQLMesh client)
- [ ] Fill in `knowledge-base/domain.md` with domain context
- [ ] Test GitHub App webhook (open a test PR, verify review comment)
- [ ] Validate framework-specific CI: dbt build OR sqlmesh plan + table diff
- [ ] Validate two-pass review triggers (pass 1 and pass 2 escalation)
- [ ] Enable `PRHealingAgent` if Pro tier

### Phase 4: Demo Readiness
- [ ] Run `ironlayer plan .` on client project — generate first plan report (auto-detects framework)
- [ ] Run full CI on a sample PR — data diff (dbt: IronLayer engine; sqlmesh: `table_diff`), lineage, anomaly detection
- [ ] Review costs: `exodus ai-usage --month`
- [ ] Client walkthrough: show AI review comment, auto-fix demo

## Terraform Provisioning (exodus-terraform)

```hcl
# terraform/clients/client-alpha.tf
module "client_alpha" {
  source = "../modules/client"

  client_id     = "client-alpha"
  client_name   = "Client Alpha"
  github_org    = "ironlayer"
  databricks_host = "https://xxx.azuredatabricks.net"

  subscription_tier = "pro"  # free | pro

  tags = merge(local.common_tags, {
    Client = "client-alpha"
  })
}
```

## Version Pinning

Clients pin to a specific Exodus Foundation version in `exodus.yml` (`platform_version`).
Upgrading: update `platform_version` → open PR → AI review validates the change → human approves.
